description: β-1,4 N-acetylgalactosaminyltransferases. In humans, B4GALNT1 is involved in the transfer of GalNAc from UDP-GalNAc into either G(M3) or G(D3) to form G(M2) and G(D2), respectively. It could also synthesize asialo-GM2 (GA2).

Beta-1,2-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferases. In humans, POMGNT1 catalyzes the addition of N-acetylglucosamine to an O-linked mannose for O-mannosyl glycosylation. Another GT13 enzyme in humans, MGAT1 caalyzes the transfer of GlcNAc from UDP-GlcNAc to the terminal α1,3-linked Man in the N-glycan initiating the synthesis of hybrid and complex N-linked glycans in multicellular organisms.

Includes multiple members involved in various functions. Most are β-1,6-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferases. Also have protein O-β-xylosyltransferase and UDP-GlcA:arabinogalactan β-glucuronosyltransferase roles.
α-1,2-mannosyltransferases. Not present in metazoans and plants. Mostly present in fungal species.
β-1,2-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferases. In humans, MGAT2 catalyzes the transfer of GlcNAc to the terminal mannose in the N-glycan chain, giving rise to the second branch in complex glycans.

β-1,4-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferases. In humans, MGAT3 catalyzes the transfer of GlcNAc to the core β-mannose residue of N-glycans to add a bisecting GlcNAc that halts expansion of the complex or hybrid N-glycan.

β−1,4-N-acetylgalactosaminyltransferase domains of mostly bacterial and protist chondroitin polymerases that are involved in the elongation of glycosaminoglycan chondroitin.

rhamnosyl and galactofuranosyl transferases from the GT2 family
ceramide β-glucosyltransferases. Generally add a Glc to ceramide forming a glucosyl-ceramide(GlcCer) which is a key precursor for the synthesis of over 400 GSLs with different sugar chain structures.

α-glucosyltransferases. 2 sequences in humans: UGGT1 and 2. They are part of the cellular machinery to detect proper folding of proteins in the secretory pathway. These enzymes reglucosylate N-glycans near the misfolded part of the protein, thus providing quality control for protein folding in the endoplasmic reticulum.

β-galactosyltransferase, β-glucosyltransferase, β-xylosyltransferase activities. Mosly invovled in lipopolysaccharide biosynthesis in prokaryotes. In humans, COLGALT1 and 2 are involved in the biosynthesis of collagen subtypes by the transfer of Gal to hydroxylysine residues of collagen.
polypeptide α-N-acetylgalactosaminyltransferases (ppGalNAcTs)
GT31 sequenes most closely related to CHSY1, CSS3 and metazoan CHPF involved in chondroitin biosynthesis.

3-β-galactosyltransferases and  β-1,3-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferases.
β-1,3-glucosyltransferases and β-galactosyltransferases.

Includse GTs with multiple activities. In humans, A4GNTvcatalyzes the transfer of N-acetylglucosamine (GlcNAc) to core 2 branched O-glycans which is an essential step for the biosynthesis of type III mucin. Another GT32 sequence inn humans, A4GALT transfers Gal to lactosylceramide and plays roles in synthesis of Gb3Cer.

β-1,3-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferases. Includes the C-terminal GT domain of the LARGE glycosyltransferases involved in biosynthesis of the phosphorylated O-mannosyl trisaccharide.
β-1,4-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferases. In humans, MGAT4 transfers a GlcNAc to N-glycans to form multiantennary complex and hybrid N-glycans.
